{"id":"2111.13584","submitter":"Ezra Yoanes Setiasabda Tjung","authors":"Ezra Y. S. Tjung and Kenichi Soga","title":"Liquefaction-Induced Dam Failure Simulation -- A Case for the Material\n  Point Method","comments":"5 pages, 7 figures, 2020 Annual Scientific Meeting of Indonesian\n  Society For Geotechnical Engineering (PIT HATTI)","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.geo-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Seismic analysis of earthen dams is paramount to evaluate the risk of\npotential liquefaction and strain softening that can cause flow failure. Even\nthough the current state of the art has moved away from the simplified\nempirical methods, modeling such large deformation flow failure remains a\nchallenge especially in light of stress/strain history-dependent materials. The\nMaterial Point Method (MPM) describes the deformation of a continuum body\ndiscretized by a finite number of Lagrangian material points moving through an\nEulerian background grid. The MPM is ideal for modeling large deformations with\nhistory-dependent constitutive models within the continuum framework. The\nupstream flow failure of the Lower San Fernando Dam during the 1971 San\nFernando Earthquake is used in this paper to demonstrate the advantage of the\nMPM, where it successfully predicted the final deformed shape.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 11 Nov 2021 07:12:47 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-11-29"}
